    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-10T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-10T05:00:00-05:00" n="381"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d381">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.516/600: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-10T17:00:00+07:00"
                            >May 10, 1939—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 10—1:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>323. Reference Department’s telegram No. 143, May 4, 1 p.m.; and my telegram No.
                    320, May 10, 2 p.m.<note n="49" xml:id="d381fn49">Latter not printed.</note> The
                    Minister for Foreign Affairs this morning orally expressed to me the hope of the
                    Chinese <pb facs="0408" n="404" xml:id="pg_404"/> Government that American banks
                    would do nothing that would assist the newly formed Huahsing Bank in Shanghai
                    which he said had been created by the Japanese as a means of attacking Chinese
                    currency.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping, Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
